Project Description:

If you choose to work on a classification problem, build multiple classifiers using all of the techniques we have discussed (decision trees, k-nearest neighbors, naive Bayes, neural net-works, support vector machines, random forests, bagging, and boosting). All models built should be tuned and thoroughly assessed using appropriate metrics. Classifiers can be assessed with classification accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, precision, recall, and area under the ROC curve. 

################################################################################
caffeine <- read.csv("/Users/sonnysparks/Documents/Tarleton Spring 22'/Data Analysis/Data_Analysis_Final_Project/caffeine.csv")
colnames(caffeine)=c("Drink","Volume","Calories","Caffeine","Caffperoz","Type")
View(caffeine)

caffeine$Type=as.factor(caffeine$Type)
caffeine = subset(caffeine,select= -Drink)

################################################################################
### Split Train / Test Data ###
################################################################################
train=sample(nrow(caffeine),round(0.7*nrow(caffeine),0))
caffeine.train.data=caffeine[train,]
caffeine.test.data=caffeine[-train,]

Since this is done in a R-Markdown document, we have to carry everything with us, such as function, library and data set. This is the reason the data is read in this way from my personal file path. Our data set is of various drinks and their caffeine levels. The purpose of this project is to classify the type of drink (Energy Drink, Coffee, ect.) based on its volume, caffeine per oz, and calories. Also in this section we made the necessary train/test splits that will be used in each model to come.

Validation Decision Trees-

###### 10-Fold CV for Rpart
folds=createfolds(nrow(caffeine),10)
accvector = 1:10
for(k in 1:10){
  temptest=caffeine[folds==k,]
  temptrain=caffeine[folds!=k,]
  tempmodel=rpart(Type~.,data=temptrain)
  predSpecies=predict(tempmodel,newdata=temptest, type = "class")
  accvector[k] = metrics(temptest$Type,predSpecies)$accuracy
}
RParM=mean(accvector)

v = (1037:1043)/1000
accvector = 1:7
for (i in 1:7){
  tempfit = train.kknn(Type ~ ., data=caffeine, kmax = 15,
                       kernel =c("rectangular","triangular", 
                                 "epanechnikov",  "biweight",
                                 "triweight","cos","inv", "gaussian" 
                                 ,"optimal"),
                       distance = v[i])
  accvector[i] = (1 - min(tempfit$MISCLASS))
}

  temptest=caffeine[folds==k,]
  temptrain=caffeine[folds!=k,]
  
  tempmodel=naiveBayes(temptrain$Type~.,data=temptrain)

Validation Naive Bayes-

# Below is for L = 2 - 20
for(i in 2:20){
  for (j in 1:4){
    disccaff=caffeine
    disccaff[,j]=as.factor(cut(caffeine[,j],i))
    for(k in 1:10){
      temptest=disccaff[folds==k,]
      temptrain=disccaff[folds!=k,]
      model=naiveBayes(Type~.,data=temptrain)
      predSpecies=predict(model,newdata=temptest)
      tempaccvector[k] = metrics(temptest$Type,predSpecies)$accuracy
    }
    mainaccvector[i-1] = mean(tempaccvector)
  }
}

Validation Bagging-

# K Fold for Bagging
folds=createfolds(nrow(caffeine),10)
accvector = 1:10
for(k in 1:10){
  temptest=caffeine[folds==k,]
  temptrain=caffeine[folds!=k,]
  tempmodel=bagging(Type~.,data=temptrain)
  accvector[k]=1-predict(tempmodel, newdata = temptest, type = "class")$error
}
BagM=mean(accvector)
BagM
[1] 0.6901639

In this section we fit the Bagging model. The model was fit with the training data and tested with the test data using 10-fold cross validation. A ROC curve was also fit for this model to access its performance.

We chose a classification problem for our project involving caffeinated drinks. All of the techniques for classification were used which include: decision trees, k-nearest neighbors, naive Bayes, neural net-works, support vector machines, random forests, bagging, and boosting. All of the models were tuned and assessed with classification accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, precision, recall, and area under the ROC curve. From the table above the two best accuracies from the models were K-Nearest and Random Forest. The results were expected based on our data sets lack of columns.

Sonny - R-Part, CTree, SVM, Random Forest, Bagging, and ROC Curves. :)
Sidney - K-Nearest, Naive Bayes, Neural Networks, Boosting, Metrics :(
